}bdf
/polyLine {
/ptsArray xdf  /v xdf  /h xdf
newpath h v moveto
ptsArray {aload pop /v xdf /h xdf h v lineto} forall stroke

/ptsArray xdf /v xdf /h xdf

/paintPoly {
ptsArray {aload pop /v xdf /h xdf h v lineto} forall closepath eofill
/arcguts {
/arcNeg xdf /endAngle xdf /startAngle xdf /htRad xdf /wtRad xdf
/yCenter xdf /xCenter xdf /savematrix matrix currentmatrix def
newpath  xCenter yCenter translate wtRad htRad scale 0 0 1 startAngle endAngle
arcNeg{arcn}{arc}ifelse savematrix setmatrix
/ovalFill {false arcguts closepath fill} bdf
/ovalClip {false arcguts closepath clip} bdf

/arcnPath {true arcguts lineto closepath} bdf
/arcFill {arcPath fill} bdf
/arcStroke {false arcguts stroke} bdf
/arcnFill {arcnPath fill} bdf
/arcnStroke {true arcguts stroke} bdf
/arcFillClip {arcPath clip} bdf
/arcnFillClip {arcnPath clip} bdf
/arcStrokeClip {
/arcNeg xdf /halfW xdf /endAngle xdf /startAngle xdf /htRad xdf /wtRad xdf
newpath
xCenter yCenter translate wtRad halfW add htRad halfW add scale
0 0 1 startAngle endAngle arcNeg{arcn}{arc}ifelse  savematrix setmatrix
xCenter yCenter translate wtRad halfW sub htRad halfW sub scale
0 0 1 endAngle startAngle arcNeg{arc}{arcn}ifelse  savematrix setmatrix
closepath clip
} bdf

/fillpat {
/pat xdf /doBG xdf /bgc xdf /fgc xdf
/y2 xdf /x2 xdf /y1 xdf /x1 xdf
x2 x1 lt {/ss x2 def /x2 x1 def /x1 ss def}if
y2 y1 lt {/ss y2 def /y2 y1 def /y1 ss def}if
gsave
x1 .10 add y1 .10 add x2 .10 sub y2 .10 sub rect clip
/x1 x1 x1 cvi 8 mod abs sub def            % x1=x1-abs(x1%8)
/y1 y1 y1 cvi 8 mod abs sub def            % y1=y1-abs(y1%8)
/xlim x2 x1 sub def /ylim y2 y1 sub def
/y 0 def
{y ylim lt
{/x 0 def
{x xlim lt
{gsave
x1 x add y1 y add translate 8 8 scale
fgc aload pop setrgbcolor 8 8 true [8 0 0 8 0 0] pat imagemask
doBG{bgc aload pop setrgbcolor 8 8 false [8 0 0 8 0 0] pat imagemask}if
x 8 add /x xdf grestore}
{exit}
ifelse
}loop
y 8 add /y xdf}

/MakeOutlineFont {
makeoutlinedict begin

/outfontdict numentries dict def
basefontdict
{exch dup /FID ne {exch outfontdict 3 1 roll put}{pop pop}ifelse}forall
outfontdict /FontName newfontname put

IsVIActive&Is the specified VI currently running?LBVWVIAcbool4Returns true if the VI is running as a top level VI.
Name of the VI to check.
Some keyboards might not have <Home>, <End>, <Page Up>, <Page Down>, or <Clear> keys.  Some keyboards do not have function keys or might only have F1 - F10.
Microsoft Windows:
Use the Miscellaneous Page of the Preferences dialog to configure F10 to behave as <Alt>.
Apple Macintosh:
Use the Miscellaneous Page of the Preferences dialog to configure F1, F2, F3, and F4 to behave as Cut, Copy, Paste, and Clear.
This ring displays the currently selected part.  The size and position of the current part are displayed below.  You can select a different part by clicking on the increment and decrement arrows, or by clicking on the part.
This is the position of the top of the currently selected part (shown in the parts ring).  You can change the position by changing this number, or by moving the part.
This is the position of the left side of the currently selected part (shown in the parts ring).  You can change the position by changing this number, or by moving the part.
This is the height of the currently selected part (shown in the parts ring).  You can change the height by changing this number, or by resizing the part.
This is the width of the currently selected part (shown in the parts ring).  You can change the width by changing this number, or by resizing the part.
This button will add the comment from the comment box to the history and close the dialog.  It is the same as hitting the Add button and then closing the dialog.
xThis button will erase the history.  You will be prompted for whether or not you want to reset the revision number to 0.
GThis button will add the comment from the comment box into the history.
/This button will hide and show the history box.
This box displays the history of the VI.  You can not edit it directly, but you can add entries to it by typing a comment into the comment box and clicking on the Add button.
This is the revision number that will be included in new history entries.  The current number is displayed in the Instrument Information dialog.  It is incremented every time you save the VI.
This is the name that will be included in new history entries.  You can change the User Name by selecting "User Name" from the Edit Menu.
This box is where you enter a comment describing the changes you have made to the VI.  When you are ready to add the comment to the history, press the Add button or select Add from the History menu.
If you check this box, you will not be prompted for a comment on the rest of the VIs in this hierarchy that are being closed at this time, even if they have one of the prompt for comment options set.
AThis button closes the Preferences dialog and saves any changes.
CThis button closes the Preferences dialog and discards any changes.
This menu selects one of the
following preference categories:
Memory & Disk
Performance Tuning
Paths
Display
Fonts
Printing
History
Miscellaneous
If you check this box, LabVIEW will deallocate a VI's data memory as soon as the VI completes.  Selecting this option will slow execution, but may help with memory-intensive applications.
5This button toggles memory compaction during runtime.
-This button toggles use of the default timer.
This is the cooperation level with respect to other applications.  A high cooperation level will cause LabVIEW to give more time to other applications but it may run slightly slower.
OIf you check this box, LabVIEW will activate disk space checking during launch.
This is the minimum amount of disk space to run LabVIEW.  LabVIEW will abort the launch if less than this amount of disk space
is available.  You can not change this value if "Use Default" is checked.
vThis button sets the Abort minimum to its default value.  You can not change the Abort minimum if this box is checked.
This is the preferred minimum amount of disk space.  If you check this box, LabVIEW will issues a warning during launch if less than this amount of
disk space is available.
tThis button sets the Warn minimum to its default value.  You can not change the Warn minimum if this box is checked.
hThis menu selects which path to configure.  The paths are:
Library Directory:  location of vi.lib
Temporary Directory:  location for LabVIEW temporary files
Default Directory:  value the default dir primitive returns
VI Search Path:  list of directories where LabVIEW will search for subVIs. This list is searched from top to bottom so the order is important.
This button sets the currently displayed path to its default value.  You can not change the currently displayed path if this box is checked.
This box displays the current value for the path that is selected in the path menu.  You can not change the current path is "Use Default" is checked.
vThis button lets you select a directory with the file dialog box.  The selected directory is placed in the
string box.
This button copies one of the special directories (or one of their recursive versions) into the string box:
<vilib>: refers to the vi.lib directory
<topvi>: refers to the top VI's directory
<foundvi>: refers to the list of directories created when opening a VI.
vThe directory shown in this string box will be put into the path list when you click on the Insert or Replace buttons.
lThis button inserts the directory shown in the string box before the highlighted directory in the path list.
kThis button inserts the directory shown in the string box
after the highlighted directory in the path list.
kThis button replaces the highlighted directory in the path list with
the directory shown in the string box.
_This button removes the highlighted directory in the path list and places it in the string box.
*This is the default color of front panels.
&This is the default color of diagrams.
This is the color of scrollbars.
#This is the color of coercion dots.
This is the color of menu text.
&This is the color of menu backgrounds.
eThis button sets colors to their default values.  Colors can not be changed when this box is checked.
This button toggles offscreen drawing.  Turning offscreen drawing on will reduce flicker but may slow the display and increase memory usage.
This button toggles the number of colors (128 or 216) shown by the
color menu.  Changes to this value will take effect the next time LabVIEW is launched.
cThis menu selects which font to configure.  The fonts are:
Application font
Dialog font
System font
TThe text in this box shows a sample of the selected font using current font setting.
CThis button sets the currently displayed font to its default value.
<This button indicates that the current font is a custom one.
VThis button brings up the font selection dialog to alter the currently displayed font.
&This option toggles standard printing.
&This option toggles printer dithering.
mThis option toggles printer font scaling.  Turning this option on may improve the appearance of printed text.
(This option toggles PostScript printing.
'This option toggles PostScript level 2.
8This option toggles Color/Grayscale PostScript printing.
$This option toggles bitmap printing.
This is the default for the VI Setup of new VIs.  If a VI has this option set, LabVIEW will add an entry to the VI's history every time it is saved, even if you do not enter a comment.
This is the default for the VI Setup of new VIs.  If a VI has this option set, LabVIEW will prompt you for a comment to add to the history whenever the VI is closed.
This is the default for the VI Setup of new VIs.  If a VI has this option set, LabVIEW will prompt you for a comment to add to the history whenever the VI is saved.
This is the default for the VI Setup of new VIs.  If a VI has this option set, LabVIEW will add comments to the VI's history when the name of the VI is changed, subVIs are changed, or the VI is upgraded to a new version of LabVIEW.
If this option is set, LabVIEW will not prompt for a user name when launched.  The user name will be set to the name entered in the LabVIEW Registration.
If this option is set, LabVIEW will not prompt for a user name when launched.  The user name will be set to the system user name.
RIf this option is set, LabVIEW will show the login prompt when LabVIEW is started.
ZThis option toggles animation of execution highlighting (showing bubbles along the wires).
KThis option toggles display of scalar values during execution highlighting.
:This option toggles the display of dots at wire junctions.
HThis option toggles the display of warnings in the error
box by default.
dThis option toggles warnings about object which are unavailable in the education version of LabVIEW.
PThis option toggles opening the control
editor with a double-click on a control.
NThis option toggles interpretation of the return
key as the end of text entry.
-This option toggles use of all function keys.
!Load VI front panels in Run Mode.
This options toggles the use of the localized decimal point.  Turning this option off will result the in the U.S. standard of using a period for the decimal point.
DThis option toggles support for the numeric keypad on Sun keyboards.
This list box contains the errors and warnings for the selected VI.  If an error is associated with an object, you can double-click on the error to highlight the object on the VI's front panel or block diagram.  You can also press return or click on the 'Find' button.
`This box shows you more details about the error or warning currently selected in the Error List.
This ring contains the names of all VIs in memory that have errors or warnings.  The VIs are ordered such that subVIs are listed before their calling VIs.  Therefore, when fixing problems with a hierarchy of VIs, you should fix those VIs that are at the top of this ring first.
When the selected error or warning is associated with an object, clicking on this button will highlight that object on the VI's front panel or block diagram.

LVINLBVW
function is the operation to perform:
opens an existing file. Error 7 occurs if the file cannot be found.
opens an existing file or creates a new file if one does not exist.
creates a new file or replaces a file if it exists and you give permission. Replacement is done by opening the file and setting EOF to 0. Error 43 occurs if the user elects to disallow the replacement using dialog.
creates a new file. Error 8 occurs if the file already exists.
open or create
create or replace
createmirefnum is the reference number of the open file. The value is Not A Refnum if the file cannot be opened.
plprompt is the message that appears below the list of files and directories (or folders) in the file dialog.
start path is the path name to the initially displayed directory (or folder) in a file dialog. The default value is Not A Path, which is the path to the last directory (or folder) shown in a file dialog.
`\default name is the initial file name that appears in the selection box of the file dialog.
pattern is the match pattern specification to display only certain types of files or directories (or folders). See the description of the File Dialog function for more information.
new file path is the path of the file opened or created. You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open or create using dialog. new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.
advisory dialog? Set TRUE (default) if you want a dialog if function=0 and the file does not exist, or if function=2 or 3 and the file exists.
don't display
TPsource is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error.
)%status is TRUE if an error occurred.
EAstatus is TRUE if an error occurred; the default value is FALSE.
ERROR40code is the error code; the default value is 0.
zvsource is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error; the default value is an empty string.
code is the error code.

advisory dialog? (display:T)"`
file path is the path name of the file.  If file path is empty (default value) or is Not A Path, the VI displays a File dialog box from which you can select a file.  Error 43 occurs if the user cancels the dialog.
0 (open) opens an existing file.  Error 7 occurs if the file cannot be found.
1 (open or create) opens an existing file or creates a new file if one does not exist.
2 (create or replace) creates a new file or replaces a file if it exists and you give permission.  Replacement is done by opening the file and setting EOF to 0.  Error 43 occurs if the user elects to disallow the replacement using dialog.
3 (create) creates a new file.  Error 8 occurs if the file already exists.
advisory dialog?  Set TRUE (default) if you want a dialog if function=0 and the file does not exist, or if function=2 or 3 and the file exists.
prompt is the message that appears below the list of files and directories in the file dialog.
default name is the initial file name that appears in the selection box of the file dialog.
start path is the path name to the initially displayed directory in a file dialog.  The default value is Not A Path, which is the path to the last directory shown in a file dialog.
pattern is the match pattern specification to display only certain types of files or directories.  See the description of the File Dialog function for more information.
new file path is the path of the file opened or created.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open or create using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.
refnum is the reference number of the open file.  The value is Not A Refnum if the file cannot be opened.
file size is the size of the file in bytes; it is also the location of the end of file.

51refnum is the reference number of the open file.
relative to beginning of file
relative to end of file
relative to current mark
pos mode specifies where the write begins relative to pos offset:
Beginning of the file plus pos offset.
End of the file plus pos offset. This is the default value.
Current file mark plus pos offset.
pos offset specifies in characters how far from the location specified by pos mode that the operation begins. The default value is 0.
\Xmark after write is the location of the character following the last character written.
IEdup refnum is a flow-though parameter with the same value as refnum.
2.string is the data the VI writes to the file.
convert eol? converts the LabVIEW end of line marker to the platform specific marker when set to TRUE. When set to false (the default value), no conversion occurs.

error in (no error)<`P
error in (no error)<@P
*Writes a string of characters to a byte stream file at the specified location; the default location is at the end of file.  The VI does incoming and internal error checking and does not write if an incoming error occurs.
refnum is the reference number of the open file.
at the beginning of the file plus pos offset.
at the end of the file plus pos offset.  This is the default value.
at the current file mark plus pos offset.
pos offset specifies in characters how far from the location specified by pos mode that the operation begins.  The default value is 0.
character string is the data the VI writes to the file.
convert eol  Set TRUE to convert the LabVIEW end of line marker to the platform-specific marker.  Set FALSE (default value) to do nothing.
dup refnum is a flow-though parameter with the same value as refnum.
mark after write is the location of the character following the last character written.

| Hx-)(I16)
Logical address to read buffer from-)(U32)
Maximum number of bytes to transfer
Transfer mode bit vector
Bit 0
0 = Abort if not DOR
1 = Poll till DOR
Bit 1
0 = Terminate transfer on END bit
1 = Do not terminate transfer on END
Bit 2
1 = Terminate transfer on LF bit
0 = Do not terminate transfer on LF
Bit 3
1 = Terminate transfer on CR bit
0 = Do not terminate transfer on CR
Bit 4
1 = Terminate transfer on EOS bit
0 = Do not terminate transfer on EOS
Bits 8 to 15 = EOS character (valid if EOS termination).*(U32)
Number of bytes actually transferred
(bit vector)
Error Conditions (Bit 15 = 1)
Bit 14
Write Ready protocol violation during transfer
Bit 13
Read Ready protocol violation during transfer
Bit 12
Data Out Ready protocol violation
Bit 11
Data In Ready protocol violation
Bit 10
Read protocol error
Bit 9
Device did not recognize the command
Bit 8
Timeout
Bit 7
Bus error occurred during transfer
Bit 6
Multiple query error occurred during transfer
Bit 5
Invalid la specified
User abort occurred during I/O
Successful Transfer (Bit 15 = 0)
Transfer aborted - Device not DOR
All bytes received
Any one of the termination received
- Successful transfer

LVINLBVWe
status is a Boolean array in which each bit describes a state of the GPIB Controller. If an error occurs, the GPIB VIs set bit 15. GPIB error is valid only if bit 15 of status is set.
GPIB status vector:
status[0] - Device Clear State
status[1] - Device Trigger State
status[2] - Listener Active State
status[3] - Talker Active State
status[4] - Attention line asserted
status[5] -
Controller In Charge
status[6] - Remote State
status[7] - Lockout State
status[8] - I/O Completed
status[9] - not used
status[10]- not used
status[11]- not used
status[12]- SRQ line asserted when CIC
status[13]- EOI or EOS detected
status[14]- Timeout occured
status[15]- GPIB error detected
GPIB error is valid only if bit 15 of status is set.
GPIB Error:
-No error
-Function requires GPIB to be CIC
-No listeners detected on write
-Controller not addressed correctly
-Invalid argument(s)
(perhaps bad address string????)
-Function requires GPIB to be SC
-I/O operation aborted
-hardware not present
-DMA error
-DMA bus timeout
-New I/O attempted while I/O in
progress
-function not implemented
-file system error
-shareable board exclusively owned
-GPIB bus error (commands)
-Serial Poll Byte Lost
-SRQ line cannot be cleared
-Unrecognized commandEAbyte count refers to the number of bytes that pass over the GPIB.
status[15]- GPIB error detectedA=data string contains count data bytes from the GPIB device.

LVINLBVWc
p c`
This integer represents a GPIB address.  The low byte is the primary GPIB address (0-30) and the high byte is either 0 or a secondary GPIB address (96-126 or 0x60-0x7E).  Use MakeAddress.vi to construct a GPIB address which uses secondary addressing.
The end of transfer mode describes the method of signaling the end of the data to the listener.  Its values are:
2 (default) DABend - Send eoi with last byte.
1 NL end - Send linefeed with eoi after data.
0 NULLend - Do nothing at end of transfer.OKdata string contains the data bytes that the VI sends to the GPIB device.

(bool) status: TRUE if an error has occurred.
(i32) code: the error code associated with an error.
A value of 0 means no error, a negative value is an
error, and a positive value is a warning.
(string) source:  an indication of where an
error occurred, usually the name of the VI.
1-(bool) status: TRUE if an error has occurred."
(i32) The error code associated with an error.  Possible values:
0  Success
-1200  Invalid syntax string
-1201  Error finding instruments
-1202  Unable to initialize interface or instrument
-1205  Invalid instr handle
-1210  Parameter out of range
-1220  Error getting attribute
-1221  Error setting attribute
-1224  Error clearing instrument
-1225  Error triggering instrument
-1226  Error polling instrument
-1230  Error writing to instrument
-1231  Error reading from instrument
-1240  Instrument timed out
-1250  Error mapping VXI address
-1251  Error unmapping VXI address
-1252  Error accessing VXIbus
-1260  Function not supported by controller
[W(string) source:  an indication of where an error occurred, usually the name of the VI.

LVINLBVWg`
Secondary GPIB address ranging from 0 to 30.  Used to form the high order byte of the GPIB address which will be accepted by 488.2 functions. The value of 31 (default) means use no secondary address. The VI places secondary address in the upper byte of the packed address.
True if either primary or secondary addresses are outside ot the range 0-31.  address error indicates whether a range error has occurred.

[W(string) source:  an indication of where an error occurred, usually the name of the VI.1-(bool) status: TRUE if an error has occurred.
(ABC) Uniquely identifies the instrument to establish communications with.  The grammar for the instrument descriptor is shown below.  Parameters are shown in lower-case and optional parameters are shown in square brackets ([]).
GPIB:   INSTR{GPIB[bd]::prim addr[::sec addr]}
VXI:  INSTR{VXI::logical addr}
GPIB-VXI:   INSTR{GPIB-VXI[bd]::logical addr[prim addr]}
Optional Parameter Default Values:
bd - GPIB board (0)
prim addr - GPIB primary address (1)
sec addr - GPIB secondary address (none)
logical addr - VXI logical address
EXAMPLE:  A GPIB instrument on GPIB board 0, at primary address 5, and no secondary addressing.
INSTR{GPIB::5}"

Causes the system to make a beep sound.  Under Windows 3.1 and on the Sun, all parameters are ignored, and a simple beep is made.  On the Macintosh, the beep is made with the given frequency (pitch), intensity (volume), and duration.$

oTNJX. If the input sequence X is empty, standard deviation and mean are NaN.
n?}I
mean
mean$
standard deviation$
standard deviation
errorX
stddevhhSB0
Computes the mean value and the standard deviation (STD) of the values in the input sequence X. The mean and standard deviation are computed using the following formulas:
mean = Sum { X[i] } / n.
STD = sqrt( Sum{ (X[i] - mean)^2 } / n ).$

\WUu
+'baud rate is the rate of transmission.
>:stop bits is 0 for one stop bit, or 1 for two stop bits.
2 bitsGCparity is 0 for no parity, 1 for odd parity, or 2 for even parity.
space paritylhdata bits is the number of bits in the incoming data. The value of data bits is between five and eight.
buffer size indicates the size of the input and output buffers the VI allocates for communication through the specified port. If buffer size is less than or equal to 1 K, the VI uses 1 K as the buffer size. You may need to use larger buffers for large data transfers.
.*XOFF byte is the byte used for XOFF (^S).
9When you use the serial port VIs under Windows, the port number parameter can have the following values:
COM6
COM7
COM8
COM9
LPT4
COM5
When you use the serial port VIs on a Sun SPARCstation, the port number parameter is 0 for /dev/ttya, 1 for /dev/ttyb, and so on.
On the Macintosh, port 0 is the modem, using the drivers .ain and .aout. Port 1 is the printer, using the drivers.bin and .bout. To get more ports on a Macintosh, you must install other boards, with the accompanying drivers.
Refer to Appendix C, Error Codes, for a list of error codes.
Some error codes returned by the serial port VIs are platform-specific. Please refer to your system documentation for a list of error codes.
,(XON byte is the byte used for XON (^Q).
Parity Error Byte. If the high byte is non-zero, the low byte is the character that is used to replace any parity errors found when parity is enabled.
uqInput HW Handshake. On the PC and SPARCstation, this parameter corresponds to Request To Send (RTS) handshaking.
Input alt HW Handshake. On the PC, this parameter corresponds to Data Terminal Ready (DTR) handshaking. On the SPARCstation, this parameter is ignored.
lhOutput XON/XOFF. See the Common Serial Port VI Parameters section of this chapter for more information.
tpOutput HW Handshake. On the PC and SPARCstation, this parameter corresponds to Clear to Send (CTS) handshaking.
Output alt HW Handshake. On the PC, this parameter corresponds to Data Set Ready (DSR) handshaking. On the SPARCstation, this parameter is ignored.

status is TRUE if an error occurred, or FALSE if not. If status is TRUE, code is a non-zero error code. If status is FALSE, code can be zero or a warning code."
code is the number identifying an error or warning. If status is TRUE, code is a non-zero error code. If status is FALSE, code can be zero or a warning code. Use the error handler VIs to look up the meaning of this code and to display the corresponding error message.
source is a string that indicates the origin of the error, if any. Usually source is the name of the VI in which the error occurred.

Port
This vi handles the RS-232 communications for a UUT. FC In and FC Out are used for flow control.
Mode 0 - Write then Read.
Mode 1 - Write only.
Mode 2 - Read only.
Timeout is in seconds.$

new file path is the path of the file opened. You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog. new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.

^Zerror status is TRUE if the error in cluster or any of the error codes reflects an error.
source messages contains the source message you want to appear in the error out cluster if the VI finds an error in error codes. Place each message on a separate line in a string constant or control.
error out is a cluster that reflects the status of the first error input that tests TRUE. It has the same elements as error in.
($status is TRUE if an error occurred."
error in is a cluster of elements that describes any previous error you want to check. If it is unwired or indicates no error, the VI checks the error codes array instead. See Simple Error Handler for additional information.

error codes
This subVI tests the error status output of one or more low-level functions or subVIs that output a numeric error code, and creates an error out cluster that can be wired to the Simple or General Error Handler in order to identify the error and describe it to the user.
You can optionally use the source messages string to pass on the source of the error. Enter one line of text for each element of the error codes array.
The error? status  is TRUE on any error.
monnie'Displayed scrollbars on source strings.
e$f$
If the error in cluster has a status of no-error, then test each element of error codes array, stopping on the first non-zero value or after all are tested; pick the selected line from the optional source messages as the error out source.
\If the error in cluster has a status of ERROR, pass it through without test for local errorsH

line mode (characters:F)<@P
Reads a string of characters from a byte stream file at the specified location; the default location is at the current mark.  The VI does incoming and internal error checking and does not read if an incoming error occurs.

character string is the data read from the file.

HDcode out is the error code indicated by the error in or error code.
=type of dialog determines what type dialog box will be displayed, if any. Regardless of its value, the VI outputs error information and message describing the error.
displays no dialog box. This is useful if you want to have programmatic control over how the error is handled.
(the default value) displays a dialog box with a single OK button. After the user responds, the VI returns control to the main VI.
displays a dialog box with buttons allowing the user to either continue or stop. If the user cancels, the VI calls the Stop function to halt execution.
no dialog
OK message
continue or stop message
exception action is a way for you to create exceptions to error handling. You can treat what is normally an error as no error, or treat a no error condition as an error using this parameter.
(the default value) performs no error exception handling.
cancels error under the following conditions:
sets error under the following conditions:
b^exception code is the error code that you want to treat as an exception. By default, it is 0.
error code is a numeric error code. If error in indicates an error, the VI ignores error code. If not, the VI tests it. A non-zero value signifies an error.
no exception
cancel error on match
set error on match
user-defined codes is an array of the numeric error codes you define in your VIs. The VI searches this array after searching the internal list of error codes. Codes in the range of 5000 to 9999 are reserved for users.
user-defined descriptions is an array of descriptions of user-defined codes. If an incoming error matches one in user-defined codes, the VI uses the corresponding description from user-defined descriptions in message.
2.source out indicates the source of the error.
}yexception source is the error message that you want to use to test for an exception. By default, it is an empty string.
error source is an optional string you can use to describe the source of error code. The VI uses the string in message if there is an error.
jferror in describes an error that you want to check. If unwired, this VI checks error code for errors.
status is TRUE if an error occurred. If this value is FALSE, then the error handler assumes that no error occurred according to the error in, and then checks the error code.
ERROR51code is the error code associated with an error.
source. In case of an error, most VIs that use the error in and error out clusters set source to the name of the VI or function that produced the error.
|xerror out contains the same information as status out, code out, and source out. It has the same structure as error in.
mimessage describes the error code that occurred, the source of the error, and a description of the error.

General Error Handler.vi7ST
-10809wD
INSTRUCTIONS:
Other Uses:
user-defined codes.  The error handler has tables of error codes and descriptions for all LabVIEW I/O operations (file, GPIB, DAQ, etc.).  You can augment the tables with the user-defined arrays.  Codes from 5000 to 9999 are reserved for user assignments.
No Error\D
\soccurred\sat\seD
.\n\nPossible\sreasons:\ndD
an unidentified locationSD
Error\sPD
StopTD
ContinueH
10000QD
#check for DAQ/Instr Driver warningsPD
6Windows GetCommError:  The hex value of this code is xH
This error code is not listed in the internal database, or you have wired a number that is not an error code (such as a DAQ task ID) to the error code input.PD
1301PD
error descriptions (hidden)O
QDSP NumBytesGTZero:  The number of bytes to allocate should be greater than zero.W
DescriptionL
[user-defined descriptions]M
[user-defined codes]{
/reinitialize to default to display instructionsHD
[error code] (0)L
[error source] (" ")L
[exception source]M
[exception code]gD
[exception action] (none:0)M
type of dialog (OK msg:1)H
QDSP NumBytesGTZero:  The number of bytes to allocate should be greater than zero.SDSP InvalidDataType:  The data type can only be 4 bytes long(0) or 2 bytes long(1).
DSP GROUP_ERR.  The function ID specified does not belong to any group that is part of the DSP Library currently running on the board.
DSP FNC_ERR:  The function ID specified does not correspond to a function that is part of the DSP Library currently running on the board.
DSP NoBrdRespToTransfer:  The DSP board on which you are trying to load the COFF file is not responding to the transfer of the file.  Check if there is a board in the slot desired and verify with the DAQCONF utility.
DSP AddrSpaceErr:  The COFF file you are trying to load is linked with a memory map that exceeds the maximum memory space allowed by the WE DSP32C chip (2^24).GDSP CoffSectErr:  Found an unimplemented section flag in the COFF file.
DAQ gpctrDataLossErr:  One of  more data points may have been lost during buffered GPCTR operations due to speed limitations of your system.
DAQ dmaChainingErr:  New buffer information was not available at the time of the DMA chaining interrupt; DMA transfers will terminate at the end of the currently active transfer buffer.
DAQ overWriteErr:  The driver wrote new data into the input transfer buffer before the data acquisition VI could retrieve the old data.
DAQ overFlowErr:  Because of system limitations, the driver could not read data from the device fast enough to keep up with the device throughput; the onboard device memory reported an overflow error.
DAQ underWriteErr:  The data acquisition VI did not write new data to the output transfer buffer before the driver attempted to transfer the data to the device for output.
DAQ underFlowErr:  Because of system limitations, the driver could not write data to the device fast enough to keep up with the device throughput.
DAQ hardwareErr:  The hardware is not responding to the specified operation, or the response from the hardware is not consistent with the functionality of the hardware.
DAQ firmwareErr:  The firmware does not support the specified operation, or the firmware operation could not complete due to a data-integrity problem.mDAQ softwareErr:  The contents or the location of the driver file was changed between accesses to the driver.
DAQ sc2040InputModeErr: When you have an SC2040 attached to your device, all analog input channels must be configured for differential input mode.
DAQ polarityConflictErr:  You cannot use this combination of scan and sample clock source polarities for this operation and board.kDAQ timebaseConflictErr: You cannot use this combination of scan and sample clock timebases for this board.
DAQ invalidReadErr:  An attempt was made to read 0 bytes from the transfer buffer, or an attempt was made to read past the end of the transfer buffer.
DAQ delayTrigErr: The delayed trigger mode is not supported or is not available in the current configuration, or no delay source has been assigned.:DAQ postTrigErr:  No posttrigger source has been assigned.
DAQ memPageErr:  The transfer buffer contains a page break; system resources may require reprogramming when the page break is encountered.KDAQ memLockErr:  The transfer buffer cannot be locked into physical memory.
DAQ or DSP memFullErr:  No more system memory is available on the heap, or no more memory is available on the device, or insufficient disk space is available.
DAQ or DSP deviceSupportErr:  The specified device does not support the requested action (the driver recognizes the device, but the action is inappropriate for the device)._DAQ deviceNotFoundErr:  No device is located in the specified slot or at the specified address.
DAQ SCXIConfigErr:  The specified SCXI configuration parameters are invalid, or the function cannot be executed with the current SCXI configuration.
DAQ dupAddressErr:  The base addresses for two or more devices are the same; consequently, the driver is unable to access the specified device.
DAQ badBufferSpec:  The requested number of buffers or the buffer size is not allowed; e.g., Lab-PC buffer limit is 64K samples, or the board does not support multiple buffers.
DAQ badIntervalErr:  The analog input scan rate is too fast for the number of channels and the channel clock rate; or the given clock rate is not supported by the associated counter channel or I/O channel.
DAQ badCountErr:  The count is too small or too large for the specified counter; or the given I/O transfer count is not appropriate for the current buffer or channel configuration.+DAQ badCounterErr:  The counter is invalid.&DAQ badGroupErr: The group is invalid.
DAQ badChanErr:  A channel is out of range for the board type or input configuration; or the combination of channels is not allowed; or the scan order must be reversed (0 last).%DAQ badLineErr:  The line is invalid.0DAQ or DSP badDeviceErr:  The device is invalid.
DAQ valueConflictErr:  The value of a numeric parameter is inconsistent with another one, and therefore the combination is invalid.BDAQ invalidValueErr:  The value of a numeric parameter is invalid.
DAQ semanticsErr:  An error was detected in the input string; the syntax of the string is correct, but certain values specified in the string are inconsistent with other values specified in the string.
LabVIEW: Argument error; that is, an input parameter is invalid.
GPIB ECIC:  Command requires GPIB Controller to be Controller in Charge.?LabVIEW:  Memory full.
GPIB ENOL:  Write detected no Listeners.KLabVIEW:  Out of zone.
GPIB EADR:  GPIB Controller not addressed correctly.ALabVIEW:  End of file.
GPIB EARG:  Invalid argument or arguments.bLabVIEW:  File already open.
GPIB ESAC:  Command requries GPIB Controller to be System Controller.FLabVIEW:  Generic file I/O error.
GPIB:  EABO:  I/O operation aborted.9LabVIEW:  File not found.
GPIB ENEB:  Non-existent board.ILabVIEW:  File permission error.
GPIB EDMA:  DMA hardware error detected.=LabVIEW:  Disk full.
GPIB EBTO:  DMA hardware uP bus timeout.QLabVIEW:  Duplicate path.
GPIB EOIP:  New I/O attempted with old I/O in progress.9LabVIEW:  Too many files open.
GPIB ECAP:  No capability.NLabVIEW:  System feature not enabled.
GPIB EFSO:  File system operation error.PLabVIEW:  Resource file not found.
GPIB EOWN:  Sharable board exclusively owned.:LabVIEW:  Cannot add resource.
GPIB EBUS:  GPIB bus error.JLabVIEW:  Resource not found.
GPIB ESTB:  Serial poll byte queue overflow.4LabVIEW:  Image not found.
GPIB ESRG:  SRQ stuck on.?LabVIEW:  Image memory error.
GPIB ECMD:  Unrecognized command.
LabVIEW:  Pen does not exist.ELabVIEW:
Configuration type invalid.
GPIB EBNP:  Board not present.ALabVIEW:  Configuration token not found.
GPIB ETAB:  Table error.$LabVIEW:  Configuration parse error.%LabVIEW:  Configuration memory error.#LabVIEW:  Bad external code format.#LabVIEW:  Bad external code offset.$LabVIEW:  External code not present.
LabVIEW:  Null window.

LabVIEW:  Null menu.

GPIB NCNT:  No count input (read).$LabVIEW:  Memory error during print.

GPIB EMOM:  Out of memory (MacBus read or write).VLabVIEW:  Device call aborted.

LabVIEW:  Generic error.%LabVIEW:  Operation canceled by user.

LabVIEW:  Message out of range.
LabVIEW:  Null method.
GPIB EPAR:  Serial port parity error.
qTCP ncSysConnAbortedErr:  The system caused the connection to be aborted.
GPIB EORN:  Serial port overrun error.
rTCP ncConnRefusedErr:  The connection was refused by the server.
GPIB EOFL:  Serial port receive buffer overflow.
aTCP ncNotConnectedErr:  The connection is not established.
GPIB EFRM:  Serial port framing error.

file path is the path name of the file. If file path is empty (default value) or is Not A Path, the VI displays a File dialog box from which you can select a file. Error 43 occurs if the user cancels the dialog.
new file path is the path of the file to which the VI wrote data. You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog. new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.
<8character string is the data the VI writes to the file.
append to file. Set to TRUE if you want to append the data to a existing file; you can also set it TRUE to write to a new file. Set to FALSE (default value) if you want to write the data to a new file or to replace an existing file.

Most applications need only connect wires to the controls and indicators displayed in bold.  Connections to other controls and indicators are useful only if specifically needed.
The Write to Digital Port VI outputs a pattern (in binary) to a specified digital port.
You can control the number of lines in a port by the parameter port width.  You also have the option of not reconfiguring the port as an output port with each iteration of the VI by setting the iteration control to a non-zero value.
Port Width for the Lab boards, SCXI-1200, DAQBox-1200, DIO-24, DIO-32F, DIO-96, and AT-MIO-16D ports 2, 3 and 4 should be at least 8.
Please read the DAQ VI Reference Manual for descriptions of Digital Port Configure and Digital Port Write for more information.$

The Read from Digital Port VI reads a user configured digital port.  The reading is displayed as a binary number in [pattern].
You have the option to not reconfigure the port as an input port by setting the iteration control to a non-zero value. You can also concatenate multiple ports to operate as one large port by using the port width paramter.
Please read the DAQ VI Reference Manual for descriptions of Digital Port Configure and Digital Port Read for more information.$

prompt.`
*Reads a specified number of lines from a byte stream file beginning at a specified character offset.  The VI opens the file beforehand and closes it afterwards.
start of read offset is the position in the file, measured in characters (or bytes), at which the VI begins reading.
max characters per line is the maximum number of characters the VI reads before ending the search for the end of a line.  The default is 0, which means that there is no limit to the number of characters the VI reads.
new file path is the path of the file from which the VI read data.  You can use this output to determine the path of a file that you open using dialog.  new file path returns Not A Path if the user selects Cancel from the dialog box.
line string is the data read from the file.
EOF? is TRUE if you attempt to read past the end of file.

MThis verison of Serial Port Reset.vi is for the Windows 3 version of LabVIEW.
This version of Set Serial Port Buffer Size.vi is to be used on the SPARC or Windows version of LabVIEW as a subVI to OpenSerialDriver and Serial Port Init.vi.
Transfers the specified number of data bytes from a Message-Based device into a specified local memory buffer, using the VXIbus Byte Transfer Protocol.
Transfers the specified number of data bytes from a specified local memory buffer to a Message-Based device, using the VXIbus Byte Transfer Protocol.
$Reads data bytes from a GPIB device.
)Sends data bytes to a single GPIB device.
Gets information about a specified device from the device information table. The information is contained in a 32-bit unsigned integer.
Gets information about a specified device from the device information table. The information is contained in a 16-bit unsigned integer.
Initializes the NI-VXI library and reads in the resource manager table. The library is automatically initialized when any VXI VI is used in a diagram. If you initialize the library with this VI, you must call CloseVXIlibrary later in your diagram.
Transfers the specified number of data bytes from a specified local memory buffer to a device, using either the VXIbus Byte Transfer Protocol (in the case of VXIbus message-based devices), or IEEE 488.2 bus Protocol (in the case of GPIB devices).
Measure volts, amps, or ohms.  Select one of 6 functions.  Select range or use auto range.  Select trigger mode.  Slow reading rate is used for accuracy.                                         version a.0
Combines primary address and secondary address in a specially formatted packed address for devices that require both a primary and secondary GPIB address.
Converts the instrument grammar to an instrument handle.  Copy or wire the instrument handle out to the instrument handle in control of your instrument driver VI to communicate with the instrument.
See the Data Acquisition VI Reference Manual for your platform for tables listing the default settings and ranges for this VI for the boards with which it will work.
Causes the system to make a beep sound.  Under Windows 3.1 and on the Sun, all parameters are ignored, and a simple beep is made.  On the Macintosh, the beep is made with the given frequency (pitch), intensity (volume), and duration.
aCompares 2 real numbers X and Y.  If they are within about 0.1% of each other a TRUE is returned.
STD = sqrt( Sum{ (X[i] - mean)^2 } / n ).
@Initializes the selected serial port to the specified settings.
QWrites the data in string to write to the serial port indicated in port number.
qReads the number of characters specified by requested byte count from the serial port indicated in port number.
kReturns in byte count the number of bytes in the input buffer of the serial port indicated in port number.
0 = com1, 1 = com2
Timeout is in seconds.
Please read the DAQ VI Reference Manual for descriptions of Digital Port Configure and Digital Port Write for more information.
Please read the DAQ VI Reference Manual for descriptions of Digital Port Configure and Digital Port Read for more information.
Output: Data written to or read from port.
FC In/Out:  Flow control terminals

\`BDHP
Setup Procedure:
1) Plug in and turn on LC103 Mainboard test box.
2) Attach power adapter and RS-232 cable to LC103
Mainboard tester (#74C216-1).
3) Connect Fluke 8840A to DVM plugs on front panel of test box.
4) Connect Lo Capacity leads to UUT plugs on front of test box.
5) Connect 50 pin ribbon cable from PC to right side of test box.
6) Press ENTER when ready, choose test to perform and press START.S

.source out indicates the source of the error.
^exception code is the error code that you want to treat as an exception. By default, it is 0.
Dcode out is the error code indicated by the error in or error code.
yexception source is the error message that you want to use to test for an exception. By default, it is an empty string.
ferror in describes an error that you want to check. If unwired, this VI checks error code for errors.
1code is the error code associated with an error.
xerror out contains the same information as status out, code out, and source out. It has the same structure as error in.
F( @L=
imessage describes the error code that occurred, the source of the error, and a description of the error.

MN <!
Astatus is TRUE if an error occurred; the default value is FALSE.
0code is the error code; the default value is 0.
vsource is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error; the default value is an empty string.
%status is TRUE if an error occurred.
Psource is in most cases the name of the VI or function that produced the error.
1refnum is the reference number of the open file.
'string is the data read from the file.
Edup refnum is a flow-though parameter with the same value as refnum.
&count is the number of bytes to read.
9EOF? is true if you try to read past the end of the file.

try to open the fileH
HD@M3
lprompt is the message that appears below the list of files and directories (or folders) in the file dialog.
\default name is the initial file name that appears in the selection box of the file dialog.
rsource identifies where the error occurred and is usually the name of the function or VI that produced the error.
scode is the identification number of the error. Use the General Error Handler.vi to get a description of the error.4#O
file path is the path name of the file. If file path is empty (default value) or is Not A Path, the VI displays a File dialog box from which you can select a file. Error 43 occurs if the user cancels the dialog.   <#
irefnum is the reference number of the open file. The value is Not A Refnum if the file cannot be opened.
Xfile size is the size of the file in bytes; it is also the location of the end of file.
Uadvisory dialog? Set TRUE (default) if you want a dialog if the file does not exist.

0LP3
spec=
Q-;A
L;qL
old.PP
code,
baud rateH
stop bitsH
buffer sizeH
XOFF byte H
XON byteH
parity error byteH
NX L
'baud rate is the rate of transmission.
:stop bits is 0 for one stop bit, or 1 for two stop bits.
Cparity is 0 for no parity, 1 for odd parity, or 2 for even parity.
hdata bits is the number of bits in the incoming data. The value of data bits is between five and eight.
qInput HW Handshake. On the PC and SPARCstation, this parameter corresponds to Request To Send (RTS) handshaking.
pOutput HW Handshake. On the PC and SPARCstation, this parameter corresponds to Clear to Send (CTS) handshaking.
hOutput XON/XOFF. See the Common Serial Port VI Parameters section of this chapter for more information.
*XOFF byte is the byte used for XOFF (^S).
(XON byte is the byte used for XON (^Q).
